{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f5c1b1b-49de-4c72-ab2e-c972f5a7771f","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.crash` or `.ips`. Open with any text editor.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Launch it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nSince NativeAOT produces a native binary (no `createdump`), macOS treats it like any other native process and generates a standard Apple crash report automatically. The `.crash`/`.ips` file will contain the faulting thread, backtrace, and register state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20ec850e-b966-496e-bbcf-d821248ccf74","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":273,"requestId":"6814:163FFF:18136CF:1B1E4EF:69FD41D3"},"id":"a4088c31-0cf6-4548-81a5-219b5379699e","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:52:28.385Z","parentId":"3e19692e-5df8-4e3e-bfbb-abda8968010c"}
